610
00:41:59,345 --> 00:42:01,030
And then you walked in.

611
00:42:01,085 --> 00:42:02,090
- Flowers?
- Mm.

612
00:42:02,091 --> 00:42:04,048
Dozens of them.
They were wonderful.

613
00:42:04,048 --> 00:42:06,195
I didn't send any. Must
have been someone else.

614
00:42:06,196 --> 00:42:07,962
I walked in and you thanked me.

615
00:42:08,180 --> 00:42:09,620
You're teasing me.

616
00:42:09,621 --> 00:42:11,741
Bloody waste of good
money, flowers.

617
00:42:12,774 --> 00:42:14,459
- You didn't?
- No.

618
00:42:17,803 --> 00:42:19,488
Really?

619
00:42:21,936 --> 00:42:23,620
Really?

620
00:42:23,784 --> 00:42:26,148
I had them at a good price.
I robbed a grave.

621
00:42:28,623 --> 00:42:30,580
All you ever think about is money.

622
00:42:30,961 --> 00:42:33,135
All anyone ever thinks
about is money.

623
00:42:48,794 --> 00:42:49,989
Don't turn.

624
00:42:49,989 --> 00:42:51,375
- Mr Simms, is it?
- That's right.

625
00:42:51,376 --> 00:42:53,550
- You came alone?
- Yes, as you instructed.

626
00:42:53,551 --> 00:42:55,752
- Everything the same on the railway line?
- All the same.

627
00:42:55,753 --> 00:42:56,759
Then it'll be tomorrow.

628
00:42:56,759 --> 00:42:59,476
- What'll be tomorrow?
- Never you mind. Here's 100 quid for you.

629
00:42:59,477 --> 00:43:01,162
Look the other way
and shut your mouth.

630
00:43:01,162 --> 00:43:02,902
- Right?
- Right, sir.

631
00:43:02,903 --> 00:43:04,914
Now, off you go and
don't look back.

632
00:43:11,819 --> 00:43:14,075
Get a bowl of water in there.

633
00:43:14,918 --> 00:43:16,413
Put it in the corner, over there.

634
00:43:16,413 --> 00:43:17,907
As far away from me as you can.

635
00:43:17,908 --> 00:43:20,355
- He's pretty heavy, ain't he?
- Pretty hungry too.

636
00:43:22,449 --> 00:43:24,296
Sorry, sir. No one's
allowed to ride in the van.

637
00:43:24,297 --> 00:43:26,852
I've got to accompany the
animal. It's very valuable.

638
00:43:29,108 --> 00:43:30,874
He gets upset if I'm not with him.

639
00:43:30,875 --> 00:43:32,560
Yeah, very well.

640
00:43:39,928 --> 00:43:41,613
Doesn't care for travel.

641
00:43:45,718 --> 00:43:47,757
- You mean it's to be you?
- Aye.

642
00:43:49,633 --> 00:43:52,486
Where'd you make them impressions?
They keep all them keys separate.

643
00:43:52,487 --> 00:43:54,172
- Do they?
- Aye, they do.

644
00:43:54,227 --> 00:43:55,912
How'd you pull 'em?

645
00:43:56,673 --> 00:43:58,358
With incredible skill.

646
00:44:14,860 --> 00:44:17,904
The next gold shipment is in
a week. This time we take it.

647
00:44:17,905 --> 00:44:20,323
Agar will replace the gold
with these lead bars...

648
00:44:20,324 --> 00:44:22,172
and throw the bags from
the train at Romney,...

649
00:44:22,172 --> 00:44:25,000
where Barlow will collect them
and then drive to Folkestone.

650
00:44:25,000 --> 00:44:26,005
Where will we be?

651
00:44:26,006 --> 00:44:28,887
In a first-class compartment
enjoying the journey.

652
00:44:28,887 --> 00:44:30,300
What happens afterward?

653
00:44:30,301 --> 00:44:31,931
We divide the gold as agreed.

654
00:44:31,932 --> 00:44:33,507
After that.

655
00:44:33,508 --> 00:44:36,036
- After that?
- Yes, after that!

656
00:44:39,354 --> 00:44:41,038
You and I will go to Paris.

657
00:44:47,862 --> 00:44:50,688
You have it all worked out. We ride
on the train and they do the work.

658
00:44:50,689 --> 00:44:53,081
They have to earn their
share, don't they?

659
00:44:53,081 --> 00:44:54,767
It's all very smooth.

660
00:44:55,473 --> 00:44:57,240
Unless something goes wrong.

661
00:44:57,376 --> 00:44:58,762
What could go wrong?

662
00:44:58,763 --> 00:45:00,312
My dear Mr Simms.

663
00:45:00,313 --> 00:45:02,025
As your humble servant,...

664
00:45:02,297 --> 00:45:04,825
I would be greatly
obliged and indebted...

665
00:45:05,233 --> 00:45:08,631
if you could contrive to meet with
me at the Palace, Sydenham...

666
00:45:08,821 --> 00:45:10,507
for the purpose...

667
00:45:11,213 --> 00:45:12,899
For the purpose...

668
00:45:13,170 --> 00:45:15,644
For the purpose of discussing
some matters of...

669
00:45:15,644 --> 00:45:17,003
mutual interest.

670
00:45:17,003 --> 00:45:18,689
Most respectfully,...

671
00:45:18,689 --> 00:45:20,456
William Williams, Esquire.

672
00:45:20,918 --> 00:45:22,604
That should do it.

673
00:45:23,501 --> 00:45:25,186
Well now, Willy...

674
00:45:25,241 --> 00:45:26,844
What's this fellow Simms up to, eh?

675
00:45:26,845 --> 00:45:28,366
Please, sir, I can't tell you.

676
00:45:28,366 --> 00:45:31,112
Should have thought of that before
we caught you with this purse.

677
00:45:31,113 --> 00:45:32,798
I don't want to go
back to prison, sir.

678
00:45:32,798 --> 00:45:34,483
Well, then. Better tell us.

679
00:45:34,728 --> 00:45:36,250
I don't know, sir. I told you.

680
00:45:36,414 --> 00:45:39,104
All's I know is that he's a cracksman
planning a flash pull, he is.

681
00:45:39,105 --> 00:45:40,789
The letter will put you on to him.

682
00:45:44,216 --> 00:45:45,629
We'll see.

683
00:45:45,629 --> 00:45:47,314
They'll kill me, they will.

684
00:45:47,613 --> 00:45:49,978
Then see you aren't
running off again, eh?

685
00:45:51,420 --> 00:45:53,892
We'll have a look at this
mysterious Mr Simms.

686
00:46:21,757 --> 00:46:23,361
Don't turn round, Willy.

687
00:46:26,787 --> 00:46:29,396
- Now, what is it?
- I'm needing a bit, Mr Simms.

688
00:46:29,994 --> 00:46:32,739
- You've been paid.
- I'm needing more.

689
00:46:33,174 --> 00:46:35,838
- You been working, Willy?
- No!

690
00:46:35,839 --> 00:46:38,068
- Did the crushers pick you up?
- I swear it, no!

691
00:46:41,194 --> 00:46:43,694
- Willy, if you've turned nose on me...
- I swear it's no flam.

692
00:46:43,695 --> 00:46:46,712
A finny or two's what I need
and that'll be an end to it.

693
00:46:47,664 --> 00:46:49,485
There's a finny in your pocket.

694
00:46:50,166 --> 00:46:51,496
You're sweating.

695
00:46:51,497 --> 00:46:53,997
If you've turned nose on
me, I'll see you in lavender.

696
00:46:53,998 --> 00:46:55,574
Not me, sir. I swear!

697
00:46:59,353 --> 00:47:01,038
Three crushers.

698
00:47:13,897 --> 00:47:15,582
Edward! Edward Pierce!

699
00:47:16,045 --> 00:47:18,545
Edward, we were wondering
what had become of you.

700
00:47:18,546 --> 00:47:20,231
I got married.

701
00:47:20,367 --> 00:47:22,052
Must dash.

702
00:47:24,118 --> 00:47:27,162
- Do you think he's in trouble?
- Wouldn't surprise me.

703
00:47:27,163 --> 00:47:30,262
Very rough man. Not
a good sort at all.

704
00:49:46,484 --> 00:49:49,011
- So, the snakesman is dead.
- I'm afraid so, sir.

705
00:49:49,011 --> 00:49:51,785
- And this fellow Simms has vanished?
- Yes, sir.

706
00:49:51,785 --> 00:49:53,633
And we don't know who
he is or what he intends?

707
00:49:53,634 --> 00:49:55,753
- We are entirely without clues.
- No, not entirely.

708
00:49:55,754 --> 00:49:59,559
We know Simms arranged for Clean Willy
to break from Newgate some months ago.

709
00:49:59,559 --> 00:50:01,951
- So it's a long-standing plan.
- A plan we don't know.

710
00:50:01,951 --> 00:50:04,561
Quite. But we do know Simms is a
safecracker. He must be after safes.

711
00:50:04,562 --> 00:50:07,823
And Willy broke into the dispatcher's
office of the South Eastern Railway Line.

712
00:50:07,824 --> 00:50:09,399
Hmm.

713
00:50:09,400 --> 00:50:12,825
And it occurred to me, could this Simms
be planning to steal the Crimean gold?

714
00:50:12,826 --> 00:50:14,647
Steal from a moving railway train?

715
00:50:15,027 --> 00:50:16,494
Who could imagine such a thing?

716
00:50:16,495 --> 00:50:18,045
The next gold shipment is tomorrow.

717
00:50:18,046 --> 00:50:20,600
I've alerted the railway line
to take extra precautions.

718
00:50:20,600 --> 00:50:22,775
- What's this?
- Precautions, sir.

719
00:50:22,775 --> 00:50:25,656
I will ride the train to Folkestone
tonight. I shall be there tomorrow...

720
00:50:25,657 --> 00:50:27,776
in case there's any tomfoolery
when the gold arrives.

721
00:50:27,777 --> 00:50:30,250
- Very enterprising of you.
- Thank you, sir.

722
00:50:30,252 --> 00:50:32,697
We've made new security
arrangements throughout.

723
00:50:32,698 --> 00:50:33,730
New lock.

724
00:50:33,731 --> 00:50:37,373
New guard, just in case they do have
the audacity to try for the Crimean gold.

725
00:50:37,373 --> 00:50:38,868
Excellent foresight, Mr Sharp.

726
00:50:38,868 --> 00:50:41,205
I must commend you on your
attention in this matter.

727
00:50:41,206 --> 00:50:43,734
We certainly wouldn't
want to lose that gold.

728
00:50:53,847 --> 00:50:56,756
It's all changed. Everything.
Everything's changed.

729
00:50:56,756 --> 00:50:59,610
No one's allowed to ride in the luggage
van save Burgess himself as guard.

730
00:50:59,610 --> 00:51:01,458
And they've got a new
jack on the platform...

731
00:51:01,459 --> 00:51:03,470
who opens all parcels large
enough for a man to hide in.

732
00:51:03,471 --> 00:51:07,113
And if that ain't bad enough, they've gone
and fitted a lock on the luggage van door.

733
00:51:07,113 --> 00:51:11,190
They're locking it at the station and not
opening it until it gets to Folkestone.

734
00:51:11,191 --> 00:51:13,882
A precautionary measure.
All on account of the gold.

735
00:51:14,181 --> 00:51:16,301
Bloody outside lock! It can't
be worked from within.

736
00:51:16,302 --> 00:51:18,421
Even if I was to be able
to get inside the van...

737
00:51:18,422 --> 00:51:21,003
I'd be locked inside there
until it gets into Folkestone.

738
00:51:21,004 --> 00:51:24,674
And who do you think's behind all this?
Only the crushers theirselves, that's who.

739
00:51:24,729 --> 00:51:26,196
Two plainclothes
jacks were there...

740
00:51:26,197 --> 00:51:29,132
saying as how a Mr Simms was
planning to rob the Crimean gold.

741
00:51:29,133 --> 00:51:32,176
They don't have a high opinion of your
intelligence. But they credit your nerve.

742
00:51:32,177 --> 00:51:35,602
And they've put crushers on every
station on the line and at Folkestone.

743
00:51:35,603 --> 00:51:37,397
So. Here we are.

744
00:51:38,838 --> 00:51:41,881
Burgess is no use. I can't get into the van
because of that jack opening everything.

745
00:51:41,882 --> 00:51:45,497
Even if I could, I couldn't get the gold
out as the door's locked from the outside.

746
00:51:45,497 --> 00:51:47,427
So what's it to have
four keys, I ask you?

747
00:51:47,428 --> 00:51:50,146
Four keys or 40 keys... it don't
make no bloody difference!

748
00:51:50,146 --> 00:51:52,810
It's a waste, the whole thing!
And nothing to be done about it.

749
00:51:52,811 --> 00:51:55,392
All on account of they found you
out, Mr Edward bloody Simms Pierce!

750
00:51:55,393 --> 00:51:58,709
That was something you didn't think of.
What have you got to say about that?

751
00:52:02,108 --> 00:52:03,793
Find me a dead cat.

752
00:52:24,453 --> 00:52:26,002
Now then, missy, now then.

753
00:52:26,002 --> 00:52:27,878
Oh, please, sir, can you help me?

754
00:52:27,879 --> 00:52:29,781
The man is a
heartless beast, he is.

755
00:52:29,782 --> 00:52:31,901
- What man?
- That guard upon the line, sir.

756
00:52:31,902 --> 00:52:34,457
He will not let me set my
dear brother on the train.

757
00:52:34,974 --> 00:52:36,767
He says it must be...

758
00:52:36,768 --> 00:52:37,827
opened!

759
00:52:37,828 --> 00:52:39,947
Why... the cruel rogue.

760
00:52:39,948 --> 00:52:41,851
We'll have your
brother on the train.

761
00:52:43,401 --> 00:52:44,460
There's, um...

762
00:52:44,461 --> 00:52:46,146
no need to open it.

763
00:52:48,810 --> 00:52:51,284
I, um... I see you have
a Bateson's belfry here.

764
00:52:51,284 --> 00:52:52,697
Oh, yes, sir.

765
00:52:52,697 --> 00:52:56,911
Me brother, he was terrible afraid of
being buried alive, so here's the safety.

766
00:52:57,564 --> 00:53:00,880
Very thoughtful, I'm sure. Just
you dry your eyes. All will be well.

767
00:53:01,369 --> 00:53:02,919
Thank you, sir.

768
00:53:02,919 --> 00:53:05,093
I'll just... get this
business finished.

769
00:53:07,975 --> 00:53:10,558
- How could you be so cruel?
- I only told her the new rules.

770
00:53:10,558 --> 00:53:13,304
- All containers to be opened.
- Yes, I know.

771
00:53:13,466 --> 00:53:16,701
Do you smell it? I think in this
case we can make an exception.

772
00:53:16,702 --> 00:53:17,544
Whatever you say.

773
00:53:17,544 --> 00:53:18,767
- Nephew!
- Uncle.

774
00:53:18,767 --> 00:53:19,800
Nephew,...

775
00:53:19,801 --> 00:53:22,981
mind your duties. Open every parcel
and make no exception. No exception.

776
00:53:22,981 --> 00:53:24,259
Yes, Uncle.

777
00:53:25,075 --> 00:53:27,575
- What's that ungodly stink?
- The, er...

778
00:53:29,587 --> 00:53:32,332
- Scheduled for the morning train?
- Yes, Uncle.

779
00:53:33,583 --> 00:53:35,894
- See that you open it.
- But, er... Uncle...

780
00:53:36,873 --> 00:53:38,558
No stomach for it, eh?

781
00:53:38,776 --> 00:53:40,651
Dear God, you're a delicate one.

782
00:53:40,923 --> 00:53:42,363
All right, I'll do it myself.

783
00:53:42,364 --> 00:53:44,049
For opened it must be.

784
00:53:45,654 --> 00:53:46,876
Oh! Oh!

785
00:53:46,876 --> 00:53:49,322
My dear brother! Oh,
Richard. Richard, he lives!

786
00:53:49,323 --> 00:53:50,872
He lives! Oh, he's alive!

787
00:53:50,873 --> 00:53:53,346
Oh, make haste. He's alive!
Oh, praise God, he's alive!

788
00:53:53,346 --> 00:53:54,460
Oh, he's alive!

789
00:53:54,461 --> 00:53:56,037
Hurry! Hurry! Lest we are too late.

790
00:53:56,037 --> 00:53:57,613
I knew it was not cholera!

791
00:53:57,614 --> 00:53:58,620
Cholera?

792
00:53:58,620 --> 00:54:00,931
He was a quack to say it.
I knew it! Hurry. Hurry.

793
00:54:00,931 --> 00:54:04,383
- Five days I've waited to hear that bell.
- You say cholera? Five days?

794
00:54:04,737 --> 00:54:06,422
Richard! Richard!

795
00:54:06,612 --> 00:54:08,297
Ohh!

796
00:54:08,760 --> 00:54:10,445
Oh, no!

797
00:54:18,356 --> 00:54:18,981
Oh...

798
00:54:18,982 --> 00:54:21,428
How can it be? I heard the bell.

799
00:54:21,673 --> 00:54:23,276
Did you not?

800
00:54:23,277 --> 00:54:24,962
I heard it plain.

801
00:54:25,098 --> 00:54:26,266
The bell rang.

802
00:54:26,267 --> 00:54:28,958
No, missy. A gust of wind
or a tremor on the ground.

803
00:54:29,421 --> 00:54:30,507
I'm sorry.

804
00:54:30,508 --> 00:54:31,948
But I heard it.

805
00:54:31,948 --> 00:54:33,905
Load this on. Sharp now!

806
00:54:33,905 --> 00:54:35,373
Come along.

807
00:54:35,509 --> 00:54:37,195
Steady. Steady now.

808
00:54:37,331 --> 00:54:39,016
Stand aside there.

809
00:54:39,153 --> 00:54:40,538
Careful.

810
00:54:40,539 --> 00:54:42,033
That's right.

811
00:54:42,034 --> 00:54:44,616
Over here. A little to
your right. Set it down.

812
00:54:44,616 --> 00:54:48,041
- There's more colour to you now.
- Yes, I feel much better now, thank you.

813
00:54:48,041 --> 00:54:49,345
- Goodbye.
- Bye-bye, miss.

814
00:54:49,346 --> 00:54:52,527
- All right for you. I'll be in here with it.
- Rather you than me, mate!

815
00:54:54,267 --> 00:54:55,952
Oh, the stench!

816
00:55:29,579 --> 00:55:31,645
- Can you do it?
- I think so.

817
00:55:31,646 --> 00:55:33,005
It's a long way back there.

818
00:55:33,005 --> 00:55:35,940
Five carriages, 30 feet each,
that's 150 feet altogether.

819
00:55:35,941 --> 00:55:36,918
I'll manage.

820
00:55:36,919 --> 00:55:39,664
- You're not going to get killed, are you?
- Oh, I'd rather not.

821
00:55:39,855 --> 00:55:40,725
Edward!

822
00:55:40,725 --> 00:55:43,443
- Edward Pierce, my dear fellow!
- Damn. Henry Fowler!

823
00:55:43,444 --> 00:55:45,102
He cannot travel in
our compartment.

824
00:55:45,102 --> 00:55:46,624
Henry, what a surprise!

825
00:55:46,624 --> 00:55:48,826
- Fancy seeing you! Are you on this train?
- Yes.

826
00:55:48,827 --> 00:55:50,321
As a matter of fact, so am I.

827
00:55:51,544 --> 00:55:54,997
Oh, forgive me. Miss Bridget
Lawson, Mr Henry Fowler.

828
00:55:55,187 --> 00:55:57,688
Miss Lawson is accompanying
her deceased brother but...

829
00:55:57,688 --> 00:56:00,624
due to the new regulations she's
not permitted in the guard's van.

830
00:56:00,625 --> 00:56:02,908
Therefore she is
seeking a compartment.

831
00:56:03,750 --> 00:56:05,300
Well, mine is available.

832
00:56:06,441 --> 00:56:08,426
Henry, you're so kind.

833
00:56:09,568 --> 00:56:11,172
You won't join us, will you?

834
00:56:11,444 --> 00:56:14,135
As a matter of fact, I've...
made other arrangements.

835
00:56:15,304 --> 00:56:16,989
Oh, I see!

836
00:56:16,989 --> 00:56:19,354
- You're quite sure?
- Oh, yes.

837
00:56:19,354 --> 00:56:21,039
You carry on, Henry.

838
00:56:24,220 --> 00:56:25,280
Miss Lawson!

839
00:56:25,281 --> 00:56:27,428
- You're in capable hands.
- You're too kind.

840
00:56:27,428 --> 00:56:29,385
Not at all.

841
00:57:04,508 --> 00:57:06,438
Open up! Open up!

842
00:57:06,438 --> 00:57:08,123
Open up, damn you!

843
00:57:08,966 --> 00:57:10,134
Are you alive, then?

844
00:57:10,135 --> 00:57:11,766
Of course I am, you damnable flat.

845
00:57:11,766 --> 00:57:14,512
- Good God, he's alive!
- Open it! Hurry up. I must be quick!

846
00:57:16,469 --> 00:57:17,964
Lift up!

847
00:57:17,964 --> 00:57:19,650
Oh, mother of God!

848
00:57:19,867 --> 00:57:21,552
Oh, the smell!

849
00:57:22,096 --> 00:57:23,781
The things I must do!

850
00:57:26,283 --> 00:57:28,783
Do you have, er...
many gentlemen friends?

851
00:57:29,165 --> 00:57:32,453
Oh, why sure enough. Gents are
ever so friendly to me, they are.

852
00:57:32,453 --> 00:57:34,628
- Me mum said I was a heartbreaker.
- I'm certain you are.

853
00:57:34,628 --> 00:57:38,542
Me mum was a heartbreaker herself.
Had many a caller, she did.

854
00:57:38,543 --> 00:57:40,119
Many a caller.

855
00:57:40,119 --> 00:57:42,104
And always with some little token.

856
00:57:42,104 --> 00:57:44,360
Me mum says a man loves
you, he shows you proper.

857
00:57:44,361 --> 00:57:46,671
- With some little token.
- Quite so.

858
00:57:47,324 --> 00:57:50,259
If you will permit me, I should be
delighted to give you a "token" myself.

859
00:57:51,482 --> 00:57:54,092
- Cor, you're a bold gent!
- I'm most serious, I assure you.

860
00:57:54,093 --> 00:57:56,294
- What, here on the train?
- Why not?

861
00:57:56,294 --> 00:57:58,740
Have you not heard of the
50-mile-an-hour club?

862
00:57:58,741 --> 00:58:01,269
I'm told it's beneficial
to the circulation.

863
00:58:10,594 --> 00:58:12,659
- But the van's locked from outside.
- It's taken care of.

864
00:58:12,660 --> 00:58:14,426
- How?
- You'll see soon enough.

865
00:58:14,427 --> 00:58:17,144
My friend will come over the top of the
train between Redhill and Ashford.

866
00:58:17,144 --> 00:58:19,265
That's the fastest part of the run!

867
00:58:19,265 --> 00:58:20,951
I suppose it is.

868
00:58:21,005 --> 00:58:23,778
What about all them bridges?
Your friend, mate, he's mad.

869
01:02:06,936 --> 01:02:08,757
- What's going on?
- Take the rope.

870
01:02:11,122 --> 01:02:12,671
- Is he up there now?
- He is.

871
01:02:12,672 --> 01:02:14,166
He's lucky to be alive.

872
01:02:14,167 --> 01:02:16,722
- Hold on.
- All right.

873
01:02:21,588 --> 01:02:23,273
Now let it go easy.

874
01:02:23,300 --> 01:02:24,986
Go on.

875
01:02:47,522 --> 01:02:49,343
I can't get over the feeling...

876
01:02:49,642 --> 01:02:51,001
You look very familiar.

877
01:02:51,002 --> 01:02:53,883
- Are you sure we've never met?
- Oh, no, sir.

878
01:02:55,216 --> 01:02:56,656
What does your mum do?

879
01:02:56,656 --> 01:02:58,477
Me mum? Er...

880
01:02:58,478 --> 01:03:00,163
She's a seamstress.

881
01:03:00,761 --> 01:03:02,446
An honourable trade.

882
01:03:02,800 --> 01:03:06,333
Me mum's made dresses for Lady
Eversham herself, I'll have you know.

883
01:03:07,748 --> 01:03:09,678
I'm acquainted with Lady Eversham.

884
01:03:10,194 --> 01:03:11,716
Oh.

885
01:03:34,715 --> 01:03:36,073
- All done?
- Done.

886
01:03:36,074 --> 01:03:38,547
Good. We've got less than a minute.

887
01:03:44,637 --> 01:03:46,376
Bloody hell, you look a sight!

888
01:03:46,377 --> 01:03:47,708
I look a sight?

889
01:03:47,709 --> 01:03:49,720
No, but you're all covered in soot.

890
01:03:51,433 --> 01:03:52,764
It's the smoke.

891
01:03:52,765 --> 01:03:55,157
- I haven't brought a change of clothing.
- That's brilliant.

892
01:03:55,157 --> 01:03:58,256
What are you going to wear
coming off Folkestone station?

893
01:03:59,534 --> 01:04:00,431
Oh, no!

894
01:04:00,431 --> 01:04:01,980
Oh, no!

895
01:04:01,980 --> 01:04:05,840
Bloody hell! You paint me green, make
me lie in a coffin with a dead cat...

896
01:04:05,841 --> 01:04:07,444
and now you strip
me bollock-naked. No!

897
01:04:07,445 --> 01:04:08,749
- Shut up.
- Bloody hell!

898
01:04:08,750 --> 01:04:10,217
Let's go!

899
01:04:22,396 --> 01:04:25,223
He'll take the river road
and meet us in Folkestone.

900
01:04:31,041 --> 01:04:34,765
Take hold of the rope. We'll be
through Ashford soon. Pull it.

901
01:04:37,103 --> 01:04:38,789
We'll pass Ashford soon.

902
01:06:05,507 --> 01:06:07,192
Best lock me up.

903
01:06:07,328 --> 01:06:10,183
- Sweet dreams.
- Not bloody likely.

904
01:06:21,355 --> 01:06:25,134
Me mum told me the best gents were the
ones to watch. Full of tricks, they are.

905
01:06:25,270 --> 01:06:30,000
I knew of one caller, wanted me to come
to a room he had, full of whips and such.

906
01:06:30,136 --> 01:06:31,331
- Whips?
- Mm!

907
01:06:31,332 --> 01:06:32,745
Can you imagine!

908
01:06:32,746 --> 01:06:33,941
Mmm.

909
01:06:33,942 --> 01:06:36,987
- Well, me mum, she told me...
- My dear, my dear, my dearest!

910
01:06:37,286 --> 01:06:38,100
Oh!

911
01:06:38,101 --> 01:06:39,787
What a man you are!

912
01:06:40,603 --> 01:06:41,852
What do you take me for?

913
01:06:41,853 --> 01:06:43,456
Aagh!

914
01:06:44,734 --> 01:06:46,419
Ohh!

915
01:07:22,792 --> 01:07:24,777
Impossible woman!

916
01:07:37,363 --> 01:07:37,960
Ha!

917
01:07:37,961 --> 01:07:40,354
Robbery indeed! The very idea!

918
01:08:33,799 --> 01:08:35,484
Arrest that man!

919
01:08:54,866 --> 01:08:57,394
The court thanks you for providing
us with so clear an explanation...

920
01:08:57,394 --> 01:08:59,134
of your manner in
committing the crime.

921
01:08:59,135 --> 01:09:01,608
I'm glad to be of help. The
police seemed to be confused.

922
01:09:01,608 --> 01:09:04,081
Do spare us your impoverished
witticisms, Mr Pierce.

923
01:09:04,082 --> 01:09:06,283
Your presence here attests
to their efficiency.

924
01:09:06,284 --> 01:09:08,213
You know, you are a
very unusual man.

925
01:09:08,214 --> 01:09:10,253
Mr Pierce, I put it
to you directly.

926
01:09:10,389 --> 01:09:12,944
Did you never feel at any time
some sense of impropriety,...

927
01:09:12,944 --> 01:09:14,684
some recognition of misconduct,...

928
01:09:14,685 --> 01:09:18,516
some comprehension of unlawful
behaviour, some moral misgivings...

929
01:09:18,517 --> 01:09:21,371
in the performance of these
various and sundry criminal acts?

930
01:09:21,371 --> 01:09:24,280
- I don't understand the question.
- Evidently not.

931
01:09:24,335 --> 01:09:26,917
Sir, it is a recognised
truth of jurisprudence...

932
01:09:26,917 --> 01:09:28,711
that laws are created by men...

933
01:09:28,711 --> 01:09:31,348
and that civilised men, in a tradition
of more than two millennia,...

934
01:09:31,348 --> 01:09:34,799
agree to abide by these laws for
the common good of all society.

935
01:09:34,800 --> 01:09:36,104
For it is only by
the rule of law...

936
01:09:36,105 --> 01:09:40,536
that any civilisation holds itself above
the promiscuous squalor of barbarism.

937
01:09:40,537 --> 01:09:42,847
Now, on the matter
of motive, we ask you:

938
01:09:42,847 --> 01:09:45,678
why did you conceive,
plan and execute...

939
01:09:45,679 --> 01:09:48,218
this dastardly and
scandalous crime?

940
01:09:51,547 --> 01:09:53,232
I wanted the money.

941
01:09:59,864 --> 01:10:01,550
He'll get 20 years for that.

942
01:10:32,514 --> 01:10:34,334
What the hell are you waiting for?


